cs.CV, cs.HC, cs.IR, cs.MM, cs.CL

This paper deals with the problem of automatically estimating color-concept associations from images. The paper uses Google Images to extract raw pixel content of the images and evaluates several methods for estimating color-concept associations obtained from human ratings. This involves image processing and computer vision techniques, which are typically covered in the computer vision (cs.CV) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the importance of semantically interpretable color palettes, which is related to human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper uses natural language processing techniques to analyze the text associated with the images, which is related to computational linguistics (cs.CL).
